    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "> ` constructor(address initialOwner) Ownable(initialOwner){ }`\r\n\r\nWe don't do that kind of constructor inheritance, because it messes up multiple inheritance very fast.\r\n\r\nImagine we do\r\n```solidity\r\nabstract contract OwnableSomethingElse is Ownable {\r\n    constructor(address initialOwner) Ownable(initialOwner) {}\r\n    // ...\r\n}\r\n\r\nabstract MyContract is Ownable2Step, OwnableSomethingElse {\r\n  // what should the constructor do here ?\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe don't want to do \r\n``` solidity\r\nconstructor(address initialOwner) Ownable2Step(initialOwner), OwnableSomethingElse(initialOwner) {}\r\n```\r\nthat would be a big mess, and it would be inefficient.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nImagine the ERC20 modules if they all had a constructor with `name` and `symbol` ...",
